gineered hybridity, these works are not only anxious but speculative. The book will be of interest to academics and students researching Gothic studies, science fiction, critical medical humanities and cultural studies of transplantation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGothic fiction (Literary genre)xHistory and criticism. 0aHorror filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aTransplantation of organs, tissues, etcxHistory. 0aTransplantation of organs, tissues, etc.xHistory. 0aTransplantation of organs, tissues, etc., in literature. 0aTransplantation of organs, tissues, etc., in motion picture. 4aGothic 2021. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 19th Century .2bisacsh  aGothic.  aaffect.  aassemblage.  abiopolitics.  acritical medical humanities.  aneoliberalism.  aprecarity.  ascience fiction.  aslow violence.  atransplantation.1 aWasson, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613287140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526132871423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526132871/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles